subSection.paragraph:
Phoridae
is a considerably diverse family of tiny flies (
0.4–6 mm
) with about 4500 species worldwide (
Brown 2022a
). The phorids have a wide array of ecological habits especially in the larval stage when they can be saprophagous, predators, parasitoids, kleptoparasites, herbivores or parasites (
Brown 2010
). Phorids are highly abundant in natural habitats and they may be among the most speciose families of flies in certain areas (

Borkent 
et al
. 2018

; 

Srivathsan 
et al
. 2023

). As usual for megadiverse families of small insects, the 
Phoridae
are largely unknown. The actual number of species is estimated as high as ten times the number of described species (
Brown 2010
), highly abundant species are still unknown (
Brown 2022a
) and new genera are frequently recognized and described (e.g., 
Brown 2018
; 
2022b
).

Besides usual morphological examination, wing interference patterns (WIPs) were checked for interspecific variation following some studies that are finding useful taxonomic information on these patterns (Shevtsova & Hansson 2011; Shevtsova et al . 2011;
Cannet et al . 2023
). The WIPs were observed and photographed according to the methodology of Ament (2021a) . In order to obtain a clearer and more direct WIPs comparison, the WIPs observed in a horizontal intermediate line between wing veins M 1 and M 2 were illustrated and compared (as in Ament 2021a ).

